(
Figs. 1–6
)

Antennular peduncle (
Fig. 3B
) folded obliquely into antennular fossae. Antenna (
Fig. 3B
) extending along lateral margin of front; article 2 subtrapezoidal, slightly narrowing distally.

Pleon (
Fig. 3A, D
) extending to buccal region, covering bases of ambulatory legs; telson (
Fig. 3D
) very broad, partially recessed into distal margin of pleomere 6.

Eyes (
Fig. 5A
) moderately small, clearly visible in dorsal view, completely filling orbit.

Maxilliped 3 (
Fig. 3B
) similar to that of females.

Thoracic sternum (
Fig. 5C
) broad. Sternites 3 and 4 fused, only slit-like incision still discernible in broad concavity at base of maxilliped 3; anteromedian part produced into broadly rounded lobe, anterolateral angle also produced to rounded lobe; lateral margins concave, accommodating coxae of chelipeds; anterior surface shallowly sulcate. Exposed parts of sternites 5–7 nearly smooth; sternite 5 posterolaterally with distinct episternite; sternites 6 and 7 each with shallow notch on lateral margin; sternite 8 clearly visible in lateral part, with concave lateral margin. Sterno-pleonal cavity deep, defined by sharply delimited margin, narrowing anteriorly, reaching anteriorly to midlength of fused sternites 3/4; rounded press button present on sternite 5 inside of cavity.

Pleon (
Fig. 5D
) moderately narrow, tapering distally from pleomere 4 to telson. Pleomeres 1 and 2 as wide, longitudinally very short. Pleomere 3 oblong. Pleomeres 4–6 all subtrapezoidal. Telson semicircular, 1.7 times as wide as long.

G1 (
Fig. 5E, F
) noticeably curved at midlength, gradually tapering, with row of sparse short setae laterally; distal part subtruncate, tip subacutely pointed. G2 (
Fig. 5G, H
) endopod somewhat flattened, tapering distally; exopod about half-length of endopod, not tapering, terminal margin rounded.
